title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: members, contributors, leaders pledge make participation community harassment-free experience everyone, regardless age, body size, visible invisible disability, ethnicity, sex characteristics, gender identity expression, level experience, education, socio-economic status, nationality, personal appearance, race, caste, color, religion, sexual identity orientation. pledge act interact ways contribute open, welcoming, diverse, inclusive, healthy community.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Examples behavior contributes positive environment community include: Demonstrating empathy kindness toward people respectful differing opinions, viewpoints, experiences Giving gracefully accepting constructive feedback Accepting responsibility apologizing affected mistakes, learning experience Focusing best just us individuals, overall community Examples unacceptable behavior include: use sexualized language imagery, sexual attention advances kind Trolling, insulting derogatory comments, personal political attacks Public private harassment Publishing others’ private information, physical email address, without explicit permission conduct reasonably considered inappropriate professional setting

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Community leaders responsible clarifying enforcing standards acceptable behavior take appropriate fair corrective action response behavior deem inappropriate, threatening, offensive, harmful. Community leaders right responsibility remove, edit, reject comments, commits, code, wiki edits, issues, contributions aligned Code Conduct, communicate reasons moderation decisions appropriate.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Code Conduct applies within community spaces, also applies individual officially representing community public spaces. Examples representing community include using official e-mail address, posting via official social media account, acting appointed representative online offline event.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Instances abusive, harassing, otherwise unacceptable behavior may reported community leaders responsible enforcement codeofconduct@posit.co. complaints reviewed investigated promptly fairly. community leaders obligated respect privacy security reporter incident.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Community leaders follow Community Impact Guidelines determining consequences action deem violation Code Conduct:

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Community Impact: Use inappropriate language behavior deemed unprofessional unwelcome community. Consequence: private, written warning community leaders, providing clarity around nature violation explanation behavior inappropriate. public apology may requested.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Community Impact: violation single incident series actions. Consequence: warning consequences continued behavior. interaction people involved, including unsolicited interaction enforcing Code Conduct, specified period time. includes avoiding interactions community spaces well external channels like social media. Violating terms may lead temporary permanent ban.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Community Impact: serious violation community standards, including sustained inappropriate behavior. Consequence: temporary ban sort interaction public communication community specified period time. public private interaction people involved, including unsolicited interaction enforcing Code Conduct, allowed period. Violating terms may lead permanent ban.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Community Impact: Demonstrating pattern violation community standards, including sustained inappropriate behavior, harassment individual, aggression toward disparagement classes individuals. Consequence: permanent ban sort public interaction within community.

title: Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct
text: Code Conduct adapted Contributor Covenant, version 2.1, available https://www.contributor-covenant.org/version/2/1/code_of_conduct.html. Community Impact Guidelines inspired [Mozilla’s code conduct enforcement ladder][https://github.com/mozilla/inclusion]. answers common questions code conduct, see FAQ https://www.contributor-covenant.org/faq. Translations available https://www.contributor-covenant.org/translations.

title: K Means models
text: simple_kmeans_db() function uses dplyr ‘tidyeval’ run KMeans algorithm. means combined dbplyr, routines can run inside database. Unlike packages use methodology, dbplot tidypredict, simple_kmeans_db() create single dplyr code can extracted SQL. function produces multiple, serial dependent SQL statements run individually inside database. statement uses current centroids, centers, estimate new centroids, uses centroids consecutive SQL statement see variance. Effectively, approach uses R translation layer, also orchestration layer.

title: K Means models
text: Thesimple_kmeans_db() approach using multiple consecutive SQL queries find optimal centers, additionally, KMeans clustering, matters order set centers passed. creates imperative find way cache current centers used long running job, case job canceled fails. Starting centers calculated last, mean re-starting job “0”, advanced, read closer, set centers. safeguard implemented function trough file, called kmeans.csv. cycle update file. file name can changed modifying safeguard_file argument. Setting argument NULL turn safeguard. file saved temporary directory R session.. example set max_repats 10, artificially avoid finding optimal means next run, “kmeans.csv” file passed initial_kmeans argument. make simple_kmeans_db() use centers starting point: second run took 7 cycles complete, adds 17 cycles initially took first example top article.
code: km <- db_flights %>%   simple_kmeans_db(dep_time, distance, max_repeats = 10) km <- db_flights %>%   simple_kmeans_db(dep_time, distance, initial_kmeans = read.csv(file.path(tempdir(), "kmeans.csv")))

title: Linear regression models
text: linear_regression_db() function can used fit kind model inside database. uses dplyr programming abstract steps needed produce model, can translated SQL statements background.

title: Linear regression models
text: lightweight SQLite database used article. Additionally, sample data set created.
code: # Open a database connection con <- DBI::dbConnect(RSQLite::SQLite(), path = ":memory:") RSQLite::initExtension(con)  library(dplyr) # Copy data to the database db_flights <- copy_to(con, nycflights13::flights, "flights") # Create a simple sample db_sample <- db_flights %>%   filter(!is.na(arr_time)) %>%   head(20000)

title: Linear regression models
text: linear_regression_db() function use formula. uses table, named dependent variable. means data preparation needed prior running model. best way prepare data modeling using piped dplyr operations.
code: db_sample %>%   select(arr_delay, dep_delay, distance) %>%   linear_regression_db(arr_delay) #> # A tibble: 1 × 3 #>   `(Intercept)` dep_delay distance #>           <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl> #> 1        -0.659      1.00 -0.00337

title: Linear regression models
text: Adding categorical variable model requires prior data transformation add_dummy_variables() appends set boolean variables, one discrete value. function creates one-less discrete variable possible values. example: categorical variable three possible values, function append two variables. default, add_dummy_variables() removes original variable. reason approach reduce number database operations. Without step, fitting function request unique values every time new model run, creates unnecessary processing. real world scenario, possible values usually known beginning analysis. good idea load vector variable can used time variable added model. can easily done using pull() command dplyr: add_dummy_variables() can used part piped code terminates modeling function.
code: db_sample %>%   select(arr_delay, origin) %>%   add_dummy_variables(origin, values = c("EWR", "JFK", "LGA")) #> # Source:   SQL [?? x 3] #> # Database: sqlite 3.44.2 [] #>    arr_delay origin_JFK origin_LGA #>        <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl> #>  1        11          0          0 #>  2        20          0          1 #>  3        33          1          0 #>  4       -18          1          0 #>  5       -25          0          1 #>  6        12          0          0 #>  7        19          0          0 #>  8       -14          0          1 #>  9        -8          1          0 #> 10         8          0          1 #> # ℹ more rows origins <- db_flights %>%   group_by(origin) %>%   summarise() %>%   pull()  origins #> [1] "EWR" "JFK" "LGA" db_sample %>%   select(arr_delay, origin) %>%   add_dummy_variables(origin, values = origins) %>%   linear_regression_db(arr_delay) #> # A tibble: 1 × 3 #>   `(Intercept)` origin_JFK origin_LGA #>           <dbl>      <dbl>      <dbl> #> 1          9.62      -10.6      -7.79

title: Linear regression models
text: One two arguments needed set fitting model three independent variables. relate size data set used model. either sample_size argument passed, auto_count set TRUE. auto_count set TRUE, sample size passed, function table count part model fitting. done order prevent unnecessary database operations, especially cases multiple models tested top sample data.
code: db_sample %>%   select(arr_delay, arr_time, dep_delay, dep_time) %>%   linear_regression_db(arr_delay, sample_size = 20000) #> # A tibble: 1 × 4 #>   `(Intercept)`  arr_time dep_delay dep_time #>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl> #> 1         -1.72 -0.000208      1.01 -0.00155

title: Linear regression models
text: Interactions handled manually prior modeling step. typical model also include two original variables:
code: db_sample %>%   mutate(distanceXarr_time = distance * arr_time) %>%   select(arr_delay, distanceXarr_time) %>%   linear_regression_db(arr_delay, sample_size = 20000) #> # A tibble: 1 × 2 #>   `(Intercept)` distanceXarr_time #>           <dbl>             <dbl> #> 1          6.77       -0.00000197 db_sample %>%   mutate(distanceXarr_time = distance * arr_time) %>%   select(arr_delay, distance, arr_time, distanceXarr_time) %>%   linear_regression_db(arr_delay, sample_size = 20000) #> # A tibble: 1 × 4 #>   `(Intercept)` distance arr_time distanceXarr_time #>           <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>             <dbl> #> 1         -2.11  0.00269  0.00650       -0.00000435

title: Linear regression models
text: Fitting model regular, categorical interaction variables look like :
